==> Returning object by VALUE vs returning object by POINTER:
-> More useful to return object by pointer because then can initialize it to null-ptr when another object has this object
as one of its member functions
--> Should learn smart pointers after this, advantage is they automatically take care of memory (learning trajectory: 
object, pointer, smart pointer)

DEBUG #1: 
your class does not have a default constructor, so it errors
So this works:
EeDistributionCreator::EeDistributionCreator(TFile* fluxFile)
    : kfluxFile(fluxFile),
      kXSecMatrix_PDG14("Test2", {2,3,4}, 6,0,10)
{
}

This fails:
EeDistributionCreator::EeDistributionCreator(TFile* fluxFile)
    : kfluxFile(fluxFile)
{
    kXSecMatrix_PDG14 = MatrixK("Test2", {2,3,4}, 6,0,10);
}

because kXSecMatrix_PDG14 needed to exist before the { } body started.
SUPER IMPORTANT:
initializer list = build the member
constructor body = modify the member after it already exists

--> I created an object called MatrixK for the cross section mapping between electron energy and neutrino energy bins
--> Now, I created another object called EeDistributionCreator, this is supposed to be a massive tool that writes all
the TH2D histograms containing the cross section matching for each flavour --> 4 flavours to the root file at once
----> This tool takes as input a flux distribution, according to that distribution it determines the neutrino energy binning
on the x axis of this matrix (the columns of the matrix) and it takes in measurements and according to that determines the 
y axis binning of the matrix (the rows of the matrix)

